Mai's stage.
London — — lay before the new British Prime Minister Theresa May was a daunting task: implementing the demands of British voters — — or more precisely, the electorate of England and Wales — — to "exit the EU" and managing the far-reaching consequences of this work.
This challenge she faced left her predecessors in recent years looking woefully inadequate.
But she may have been able to complete this task.
Anybody should not underestimate May.
Like Merkel, who has already proven her courage in a series of crises, everything needed to complete the task is in May's hands.
She is smart, resilient, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideological bias, very skilled at grasping control, and operates within her own defined boundaries to ensure she is familiar with the issues at hand.
May won most of the battles she participated in and showed no mercy to those who had once used underhanded means to deal with her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination – she needs to fully exploit it to lead Britain out of the EU.
The Brexit process has already begun, this is beyond doubt.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland voted to remain in the EU, May had repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated "Brexit means Brexit," and her cabinet ministers have all backed her on this view.
But May has yet to give a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone telling you, "Breakfast is breakfast," then starting to prepare your food.
You'd have trouble figuring out exactly what you'd be served.
A traditional Northern Irish "Ulster fry" – scrambled eggs, bacon, sausages, black pudding, potatoes, and soda bread, accompanied by fried tomatoes – with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on the environment you're in and your personal preferences, you may find one combination far more appealing than another.
The same applies to Britain's withdrawal from the EU.
Some people may be primarily concerned with preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Some people are more concerned with securing access to the single market.
But unlike breakfast, the British cannot order every item on the menu.
Brexit supporters often overlook the reality that the EU will not give Britain the benefits for free.
This is not because EU leaders want to win over the hearts of people or punish the UK for refusing to join the EU, although such inflammatory rhetoric has been prevalent at times, such as when the new British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson said "Nazi-style imperialism".
Unlike breakfast, we British often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own sworn interests to protect, whether political or commercial.
For May, the core challenge over the coming months will be to define what Britain's objectives should be after the difficult negotiations with the EU on their relationship (which in the trade sphere involves the world at large) have begun on a realistic basis.
Given the complexity of the agenda, which involves at least six major themes that need to be negotiated separately, the negotiating process may take several years to complete.
By the time the negotiations are completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be in university.
We must define our priorities in order to prevent the negotiating period from lasting even longer.
The objective, of course, is to strike a balance between allowing British goods and services, particularly financial services, to enter other European countries and restricting EU citizens from entering the UK.
Negotiators gain more in one area, but have to make greater concessions in others.
May must fully utilize her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiating deal.
But even if she succeeds in achieving her objectives, she will still find that not only is there discontent among some of the population – a result that is unavoidable – but among all of it.
This will further exacerbate another major challenge facing May's government: narrowing the growing chasm in British society exposed by Brexit.
Working-class people in northern and central England are the mainstay of the Leave campaign, having long been alienated from the political elite, neglected by globalization, and marginalized by the EU, the supposed proxy of globalization.
Large cities in England – particularly London – may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have derived no benefit from it.
Due to a lack of confidence in left-wing leaders Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party, many working-class people were ultimately preyed upon by the populist promises of the Brexit supporters.
"We will turn back globalization," they claim.
"We will drive out low-wage migrants and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds that were previously given to the EU to public services."
They pledged that Brexit would allow Britain to revisit a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly deliver on these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, and similarly, it is impossible to sever ties with EU immigrants.
Any such action will only destroy British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decline in immigration, workers who voted for Brexit may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and public services remain under pressure.
This is unlikely to boost social cohesion.
Brexit has unleashed a populist sentiment storm that is difficult to control.
Just as Donald Trump has been unable to improve the fortunes of working-class American voters who supported him, Brexit will ultimately prove to be of no benefit to those who chose it.
Although possessing many advantages, May may still struggle to overcome this challenge.
